The project ?Support for Beginning Investigators to Attend the 16th SEDI Symposium? helped to support fourteen US-based beginning investigators (graduate students and post-doctoral fellows) to attend the 16th Symposium on Study of Earth?s Deep Interior (SEDI). The meeting was held in Edmonton, Alberta, Canada from July 8-13, 2018. SEDI is a committee of the International Union of Geology and Geophysics.



The biennial SEDI meetings are small, typically 15-200 participants, and they bring together international researchers focused on the Earth and planetary interiors. Researchers from a range of disciplines-geochemistry, geodynamics, geomagnetism, mineral physics, and seismology, and from a range of approaches-observational, experimental, numerical, and theoretical, are represented.



The meetings are organized around eight sessions, only one running at a time:





Mantle Structure   and Composition;

Mantle History and   Dynamics; 

Core-Mantle   Boundary; 

Outer Core   Observations, Structure, Composition; 

Outer Core   Dynamics and Modelling; 

Inner Core;

Experiments; 

Other Planets,   Observations &amp; Modelling.



Each session is   led by a longer review talk, ideally accessible to all. This is followed by   two shorter research talks, highlighting recent advances that are of   significant interest (as decided by a scientific advisory panel). Each   session then has poster viewing, followed by session discussion time. This   format is ideal for beginning investigators because they not only have the   chance to present and explain their own work, but to listen to and   participate in discussion with more senior colleagues. SEDI meetings are thus   helping to prepare the next generation of deep Earth scientists, who can help   us to understand how the Earth has and is evolving. 







